<subSubSection pageId="22" pageNumber="23" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="22.[151,1437,1369,2009]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,322,1441,1468]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Strongly furrowed with long anterior cranidial border occupying 62% (60â€“66) of short frontal area. Tips of posterolateral projection strongly deflected backward. Pygidial border furrow nearly effaced; border flexed steeply downward.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="22" pageNumber="23" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="22.[151,1437,1369,2009]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,332,1549,1576]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Discussion.</emphasis>
Opinions on 
<taxonomicName authority="Lochman" authorityName="Lochman, in Lochman &amp; Duncan" authorityYear="1944" box="[491,717,1550,1576]" class="Trilobita" family="Asaphiscidae" genus="Blountina" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ptychopariida" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[491,601,1550,1576]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Blountina</emphasis>
Lochman
</taxonomicName>
have varied. 
<bibRefCitation author="Shaw, A. B." box="[875,1022,1549,1576]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" pagination="458 - 483" refId="ref24002" refString="Shaw, A. B. (1952) Paleontology of Northwestern Vermont: II. Fauna of the Upper Cambrian Rockledge Conglomerate near St. Albans. Journal of Paleontology, 26, 458 - 483." type="journal article" year="1952">Shaw (1952)</bibRefCitation>
considered the genus to be a junior synonym of 
<taxonomicName authority="Raymond 1937" authorityName="Raymond" authorityYear="1937" box="[292,613,1586,1612]" class="Trilobita" family="Kingstoniidae" genus="Protillaenus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ptychopariida" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[292,429,1586,1612]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Protillaenus</emphasis>
Raymond 1937
</taxonomicName>
, whereas 
<bibRefCitation author="Rasetti, F." box="[724,883,1585,1612]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" pagination="1266 - 1269" refId="ref23835" refString="Rasetti, F. (1956) Revision of the trilobite genus Maryvillia Walcott. Journal of Paleontology, 30, 1266 - 1269." type="journal article" year="1956">Rasetti (1956)</bibRefCitation>
treated both 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lochman, in Lochman &amp; Duncan" authorityYear="1944" box="[1032,1142,1586,1612]" class="Trilobita" family="Asaphiscidae" genus="Blountina" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ptychopariida" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1032,1142,1586,1612]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Blountina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Raymond" authorityYear="1937" box="[1198,1335,1586,1612]" class="Trilobita" family="Kingstoniidae" genus="Protillaenus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ptychopariida" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1198,1335,1586,1612]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Protillaenus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as synonyms of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Walcott" authorityYear="1916" box="[250,368,1622,1648]" class="Trilobita" family="Kingstoniidae" genus="Maryvillia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ptychopariida" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[250,368,1622,1648]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Maryvillia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Restudy of the 
<typeStatus box="[554,602,1623,1649]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">type</typeStatus>
species, 
<taxonomicName authority="Lochman" authorityName="Lochman, in Lochman &amp; Duncan" authorityYear="1944" box="[705,1035,1622,1648]" class="Trilobita" family="Asaphiscidae" genus="Blountina" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ptychopariida" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="eleanora">
<emphasis box="[705,922,1622,1648]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Blountina eleanora</emphasis>
Lochman
</taxonomicName>
(Pls 26, 27), shows that it lacks the synapomorphies of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Walcott" authorityYear="1916" box="[370,488,1658,1684]" class="Trilobita" family="Kingstoniidae" genus="Maryvillia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ptychopariida" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[370,488,1658,1684]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Maryvillia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(see above) and the structure of the cladogram allows 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lochman, in Lochman &amp; Duncan" authorityYear="1944" box="[1091,1201,1658,1684]" class="Trilobita" family="Asaphiscidae" genus="Blountina" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ptychopariida" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1091,1201,1658,1684]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Blountina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
to be retained for the present as a monotypic genus. A broader analysis of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kobayashi" authorityYear="1933" box="[743,900,1694,1720]" class="Trilobita" family="Kingstoniidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ptychopariida" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Kingstoniidae</taxonomicName>
may help clarify its status. Cranidial characters that might diagnose 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lochman, in Lochman &amp; Duncan" authorityYear="1944" box="[383,493,1730,1756]" class="Trilobita" family="Asaphiscidae" genus="Blountina" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ptychopariida" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[383,493,1730,1756]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Blountina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
include a long anterior border occupying slight more than 60% of the short frontal area, and strongly deflected tips of the posterolateral projection. The grade of effacement of the pleural field and border furrow of the pygidium (Pl. 27) resembles the condition in 
<taxonomicName box="[900,1023,1803,1828]" genus="Kingstonia" kingdom="Plantae" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[900,1023,1803,1828]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Kingstonia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(e.g., 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Rasetti" authorityYear="1946" box="[1095,1237,1803,1829]" class="Trilobita" family="Kingstoniidae" genus="Blountia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ptychopariida" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gaspensis">
<emphasis box="[1095,1114,1803,1828]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">K</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1128,1237,1803,1828]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">gaspensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; Fig. 1.6, 1.7), as does the strong downward flexure of the border. Although the pygidial axis is mostly effaced in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Rasetti" authorityYear="1946" box="[1223,1365,1839,1865]" class="Trilobita" family="Kingstoniidae" genus="Blountia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ptychopariida" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gaspensis">
<emphasis box="[1223,1242,1839,1864]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">K</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1256,1365,1839,1864]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">gaspensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, other species retain a convex axis similar to that of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lochman, in Lochman &amp; Duncan" authorityYear="1944" box="[662,793,1874,1901]" class="Trilobita" family="Asaphiscidae" genus="Blountina" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ptychopariida" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="eleanora">
<emphasis box="[662,679,1875,1900]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">B</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[693,793,1874,1900]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">eleanora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(e.g., 
<bibRefCitation author="Rasetti, F." box="[863,1007,1874,1900]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" pagination="442 - 446" refId="ref23810" refString="Rasetti, F. (1946) Early Upper Cambrian trilobites from western Gaspe. Journal of Paleontology, 20, 442 - 446." type="journal article" year="1946">Rasetti 1946</bibRefCitation>
, pl. 69, fig. 31).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="22.[151,1437,1369,2009]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">
<taxonomicName authority="Lochman in Lochman &amp; Duncan" authorityName="Lochman, in Lochman &amp; Duncan" authorityYear="1944" box="[199,824,1910,1937]" class="Trilobita" family="Asaphiscidae" genus="Blountina" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ptychopariida" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="triangularis">
<emphasis box="[199,450,1910,1936]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Blountina triangularis</emphasis>
Lochman in Lochman &amp; Duncan
</taxonomicName>
is closely related to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Walcott" authorityYear="1916" box="[1052,1150,1911,1937]" class="Trilobita" family="Kingstoniidae" genus="Maryvillia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ptychopariida" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="arion">
<emphasis box="[1052,1075,1911,1936]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">M</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1089,1150,1911,1936]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">arion</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[1164,1232,1910,1936]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1743,1768]" captionTargetBox="[164,1423,184,1714]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[164,1423,179,1722]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 2. Phylogenetic analysis of Blountia and related taxa. 1. Strict consensus of six trees of length 30 (CI, 0.50; RI, 0.62; RC, 0.31). Names of species from Steptoean strata are identified by bold font. 2. Optimized character distribution plotted on one of the most parsimonious trees. Only unambiguous transformations (i.e., optimize to the same nodes under the assumptions of ACCTRAN and DELTRAN) are shown; open circles indicate characters that are homoplastic. Numbers above the circles refer to characters and those below identify particular states (Table 2)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3927098" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3927098/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
), and both species are assigned to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Walcott" authorityYear="1916" box="[323,441,1946,1972]" class="Trilobita" family="Kingstoniidae" genus="Maryvillia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ptychopariida" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[323,441,1946,1972]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Maryvillia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as revised in this study (see discussion above). 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Raymond" authorityYear="1937" box="[973,1110,1946,1972]" class="Trilobita" family="Kingstoniidae" genus="Protillaenus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ptychopariida" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[973,1110,1946,1972]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Protillaenus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is based on poorly preserved material (e.g., 
<bibRefCitation author="Shaw, A. B." box="[314,442,1981,2008]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" pagination="458 - 483" refId="ref24002" refString="Shaw, A. B. (1952) Paleontology of Northwestern Vermont: II. Fauna of the Upper Cambrian Rockledge Conglomerate near St. Albans. Journal of Paleontology, 26, 458 - 483." type="journal article" year="1952">Shaw 1952</bibRefCitation>
, pl. 57, figs 14, 15), and the name is best restricted to the 
<typeStatus box="[1088,1151,1983,2009]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">types</typeStatus>
.
</paragraph>
